NAIROBI - Kenya's inflation rose in May, driven by higher food prices, the statistics office said on Wednesday.The year-on-year inflation rate rose to 11.7 percent in May from 11.48 percent in April, The Kenya National Bureau of Statistics said in a statement, with food and non-alcoholic beverage prices up 1.26 percent from April and up 21.52 percent compared with May 2016.READ: Kenya s economy projected to grow 5.9 percent, World BankThe rate first rose outside of the government's preferred band of 2.5-7.5 percent in February after food prices were driven higher by a drought that left about 2.7 million people in need of food aid.Month-on-month inflation eased to 0.75 percent from 1.79 percent last month.Policy makers held the benchmark lending rate at 10 percent this week, saying its policy stance had reduced the threat of demand-driven inflation.Reuters